      </table>

      <p>The <strong>CalDigit TS4</strong> costs $100 more and gives you two extra Thunderbolt 4 ports, an SD and microSD reader, more USB-A ports, and 98W charging. It is the dock to buy if you need every port — but it is also larger, heavier, and pricier. See our <a href="/reviews/caldigit-ts4-review/">CalDigit TS4 review</a> for the full breakdown.</p>

      <p>The <strong>Plugable USB-C Triple</strong> at $199 is a USB-C dock (not Thunderbolt) that uses DisplayLink to drive three displays over a single USB-C cable. It is the right pick for laptops without Thunderbolt — including many Windows ultrabooks and older MacBooks. It cannot match the Satechi's 40Gbps storage bandwidth, but it costs $100 less and supports more displays. See our <a href="/reviews/plugable-usb-c-triple-review/">Plugable USB-C Triple review</a> for the full breakdown.</p>

      <p>If you want a smaller, more portable hub rather than a full dock, our <a href="/reviews/best-usb-c-hub-macbook/">USB-C hub roundup</a> covers lighter alternatives that travel in a laptop bag.</p>

      <h2 id="buying-advice">Buying Advice</h2>
      <p>Buy the Satechi Thunderbolt 4 Dock if you have a Thunderbolt 4 (or Thunderbolt 3) laptop and want a clean, compact dock for dual 4K monitors, fast storage, and single-cable charging. For $299 it delivers the full Thunderbolt 4 pipeline with excellent reliability.</p>

      <p>Confirm your laptop supports Thunderbolt before buying. A USB-C only laptop will not get 40Gbps bandwidth, dual 4K output, or Thunderbolt daisy-chaining from this dock — it will fall back to USB-C speeds and a single display. If your laptop lacks Thunderbolt, the <a href="/reviews/plugable-usb-c-triple-review/">Plugable USB-C Triple</a> is a better match for $100 less.</p>

      <p>Buy a longer Thunderbolt 4 cable if you want the dock further than 0.8 meters from your laptop. The included cable is short, which is fine for a desk where the dock sits next to the laptop, but limits placement. A 2-meter active Thunderbolt 4 cable costs $30 to $50 and unlocks more desk layouts.</p>

      <p>Skip the Satechi if you need an SD card reader, more than three downstream Thunderbolt ports, or a dock for a high-wattage Windows workstation laptop. The <a href="/reviews/caldigit-ts4-review/">CalDigit TS4</a> at $399 is the better pick in all three cases — it has the card reader, two extra TB4 ports, and 98W charging.</p>

      <p>Pair the Satechi dock with a fast <a href="/reviews/best-external-ssd-backup/">external NVMe SSD</a> to take full advantage of the 40Gbps bandwidth, and a <a href="/reviews/best-monitor-light-bar/">monitor light bar</a> to reduce eye strain at your docked desk.</p>

